Subject:    <a href="?t=95837888500016&r=1&w=2">Is anyone using MB/MR/MG/MINFO records yet?</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837784000019&r=1&w=2">Rob Austein &lt;SRA () XX ! LCS ! MIT ! EDU&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198610">1986-10-14 11:28:00</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026800&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026800&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Well, one use for MB/MR records is following forwarding trails with as
little overhead as possible.  People seem to leave trails from machine
A to machine B and from B to C and C to D.  Rather than have the
message have to make all those hops, you can track it all down with
(hopefully) fast UDP transactions then just send the message off to
the final destination.

There is also the distributed mail system approach.  Ie, you can send
mail to me as "SRA@LCS.MIT.EDU" without having to know which machine
at LCS I use to read my mail.  In the long run this will probably be
of major importance as more and more of our users switch to
workstations.

--Rob

